 

 1. What is a cell in Google Sheet?
   A cell is the smallest individual unit in Google Sheets - the intersection point where one column meets one row. It's a rectangular box that holds:

   Data: Text, numbers, dates, currency

   Formulas: =SUM(A1:A10), =A1+B1

   Formatting: Colors, fonts, borders, alignment

Visual Structure:

text

  A   B   C

1 [ ] [ ] [ ]  ← Row 1

2 [ ] [ ] [ ]  ← Row 2 (Cell B2 is column B + row 2)

3 [ ] [ ] [ ]  ← Row 3

Total cells: 18,278 columns × 1,048,576 rows = ~19 billion cells per sheet!


 2. How can you identify a cell address?
   Cell Address = Column Letter(s) + Row Number

text

A1     ← Column A, Row 1 (Top-left cell)

B2     ← Column B, Row 2

Z10    ← Column Z, Row 10

AA100  ← Column AA, Row 100

ZZZ999 ← Column ZZZ, Row 999

How to see current cell address:

   Name Box (top-left corner): Shows active cell address

   Click any cell: Address appears in Name Box

   Ctrl+G (Windows) / Cmd+G (Mac): Go To dialog shows address

   Formula bar: Shows cell content + address

Pro Tip: F5 = Go To specific cell by typing address!


 3. Can a cell hold both text and numbers together?

	YES, but with specific formats:


| Type           | Examples                          | How it works                                |

| -------------- | --------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------- |

| Text + Numbers | "Q1 Sales: 1500", "$5,000 profit" | Text format - numbers as characters         |

| Mixed Formula  | ="Total: "&SUM(A1:A10)            | Formula returns text                        |

| Number Format  | 1,234.56, $1,234.56               | Display formatting - actual value is number |

| Date/Time      | 1/15/2026 14:30                   | Special number format                       |


Cell A1: "Sales: 1500 units"

Cell B1: =A1+100  ❌ ERROR (#VALUE!)

Cell C1: ="₹"&5000  ✅ "₹5000"



Key Rule: Text + Number = Text, Number + Number = Number


 4. What is the use of merging cells?

	Merging combines multiple adjacent cells into one larger cell for:


| Use Case        | Example                           | Benefit            |

| --------------- | --------------------------------- | ------------------ |

| Headers/Titles  | Merge A1:D1 for "Monthly Report"  | Visual hierarchy   |

| Centered Labels | Merge A10:B10 for "Total"         | Perfect alignment  |

| Report Layout   | Merge A1:A3 for company logo      | Design consistency |

| Form Layouts    | Merge B2:D2 for "Enter Name Here" | Clean input areas  |


How to Merge:

    Select cells → Format → Merge cells

    Shortcuts: Alt+O, M (Windows), Cmd+Shift+M (Mac)

    Types:



1.        Merge all (default)
   
2.        Merge horizontally
   
3.        Merge vertically
   
4.        Unmerge


⚠️ Warning: Merged cells cause problems with sorting/filtering/charts!


 5. How can you enter a formula inside a cell?

Method 1: Manual Entry


1. Click cell (e.g., B2)

2. Type: =SUM(A1:A10)    ← ALWAYS starts with =

3. Press ENTER


Method 2: Auto-complete


Type: =SU → Select SUM from dropdown → Tab

Type: =A1+A2 → Reference appears automatically


Method 3: Function Wizard

Insert → Function → SUM → Select range → Done


Common Formula Patterns:

Basic Math:           =A1+A2, =B1B2

SUM Range:           =SUM(A1:A10)

AVERAGE:             =AVERAGE(B1:B5)  

IF Condition:        =IF(A1>100, "Pass", "Fail")

VLOOKUP:             =VLOOKUP(C1, A1:B10, 2, FALSE)

TODAY/DATE:          =TODAY(), =NOW()

CONCATENATE:         ="Total: "&SUM(A1:A10)


Pro Tips:


🔥 Double-click cell → Edit formula directly

🔥 F2 = Edit active cell formula

🔥 Ctrl+` = Show all formulas (not results)

🔥 Alt+T,U,F = Paste formula only (no values)


Golden Rule: Every formula starts with = - otherwise treated as TEXT! 🚀



